 theorist Rinaldo Walcott (Canada) asks us to consider inheritances beyond white supremacist logics: “What might it mean to live a life, if we can’t risk desiring and working towards utopia?” As each alchemist considers the legacies of anticolonial struggle, the future of the planet, and the textures of Black and Indigenous life, their essays speak to each other in multiple ways, creating something startling and revelatory: a vision of the world as it is, and as it could be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBoundaries (Philosophy). 0aDecolonization. 0aEthnicity. 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAdeyemo, Dele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiaz, Natalie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDiaz, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKisukidi, Nadia Yala, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKisukidi, Nadia Yala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharpe, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalcott, Rinaldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059769?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059769/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles